reference_notes: [Mölk Ulrich. Lohier et Malart. Fragment d'une chanson de geste disparue. In: Romania, tome 110 n°439-440, 1989. pp. 466-492.]
review_note: This cycle can be debated, but, as is shown by Mölk and others, it existed in several (now lost) French manuscripts, and was also translated into German by Elisabeth de Lorraine/Nassau. Louis, son of Charlemagne, is the link between several of the texts, in particular Reine Sebile (his mother); Lohier et Malart (conflict between his brother Lothar and him) and Hugues Capet (who obtains the crown from Louis). I invented the name, in the absence of received names for this cycle. The stories contained are marked by adventures, seduction, female characters, and other features of later chansons de geste. Several of them also feature a secondary link to Byzantine Matter.
